\begin_layout Section*
Limited Variables
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A common way to model limited variables is stated in Deaton (Essays) and
 Lee-Pitt.
 Deaton's show a modified cost-function that considers 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

rationed
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 demand - i.e.
 the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

 that are constrained due to factors outside the consumer's choice.
 This revisits the idea of virtual price (see Rothbarth)
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

and models the selection equation so that a consumer consumes an item only
 when the price is lower than the virtual price.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

 be the quantity demanded of the constrained good 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in\{1,2,3,...\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{0}$
\end_inset

 the quantity of the rationed good that is constrained to 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is the total consumption (
\begin_inset Formula $x=p_{0}q_{0}+pq)$
\end_inset

 .
 Further, utility 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $u=\nu(q_{0},q)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
If we assume separability of utility between the rationed and non-rationed
 good, we can write 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}=g_{i}^{*}(x,z,p_{0},p)=f_{i}(x-p_{0}z,p)$
\end_inset

.
 However, separability assumption is unrealistic in most situations e.g.
 with unemployment being treated as a rationed consumption of leisure.
 Status utility cannot be considered separable from non-status utility in
 a similar manner.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The rationed and unrationed problems are 
\begin_inset Formula $max\ u=\nu(q_{0},q)\ s.t.\ p_{0}q_{0}+pq=x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $max\ u=\nu(q_{0},q)\ s.t.\ p_{0}q_{0}+pq=x$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{0}=z$
\end_inset

 whose solutions can be represented as 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x,p_{0},p)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{*}(x,z,p_{0},p)$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 In the dual problem the unrationed and rationed cost-functions are 
\begin_inset Formula $c(u,p_{0},p)=min_{q_{0},q}\ p_{0}q_{0}+pq=x\ s.t.\ \nu(q_{0},q)\ge u$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c(u,p_{0},p,z)=min_{q}\ p_{0}z+pq=x\ s.t.\ \nu(z,q)\ge u$
\end_inset

.
 It is clear to see that 
\begin_inset Formula $c(u,p_{0},p)=min_{z}\ c^{*}(u,p_{0},p,z)$
\end_inset

.
 Further, a virtual price 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}^{*}=\xi_{0}(u,z,p)$
\end_inset

 is a price at which the consumer would buy the quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 of the rationed good (as if the ration weren't imposed
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Such a price must exist due to convex preferences.
\end_layout

\end_inset

).
 Thus we have 
\begin_inset Formula $z=\frac{\partial c(u,p_{0}^{*},p)}{\partial p_{0}}$
\end_inset

.
 These can be used to derive regression equations relating 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 with the ration 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 and price.
 Since we don't have prices available, we limit ourselves to the cross-sectional
 analysis.
 A more relevant approach is the selection model proposed by Heckman.
 What we take away from the analysis is that ration does appear on the RHS
 of the regression equation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Heckman approach uses a selection equation to adjust the non-normal
 truncation of the control variables.
 In the demand equation, 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{i}=ln(x_{i})+\sum_{j}P_{j}+ln(x_{i}/P)$
\end_inset

, the measure 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{i}$
\end_inset

 already accounts for quality (see Nelson's clarification and comment on
 the methods adopted by Deaton and Cox-Wohlgenant) i.e.
 an item with a higher price but consumed in the same quantity would exhibit
 a higher 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 To address the quality concerns, we need a two equation model so that the
 status parameters are introduced in the estimation.
 This is assisted with a long literature on quality (since Houthakker).
 The limited variables enter into the equation not through 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 (which is always positive as long as there is some consumption in the category)
 but through quality or status measures - as there would be many consumers
 who completely forgo a certain parameter (e.g.
 meat in food, car in transport etc.).
\end_layout

