\begin_layout Standard
Our goal is to put status measure as the second equation in a similar manner.
 We use the Heckmann selection in STATA to achieve the solution to simultaneous
 equations (notice ours is a not a a case of censoring of the quality variable).
 The choice of a selection equation depends on the limited variable - which
 in our case is the quality.
 Looking at energy for example, the quality variable can be modeled as a
 dummy variable for electricity.
 Most people won't have any electricity.
 The STATA version of Heckman selection (heckman command) deals with the
 dependent variable being non-normal i.e.
 truncated or limited so that the rule of truncation is known and thus the
 effect of truncation on estimation can be measured.
 Thus the has_electricity variable would be the dependent variable in both
 the selection and the regression equation.
 The consumption on electricity may be missing because of neighbourhood
 - just the way the meat consumption could be missing because of being in
 a low income band and/or region (which is a proxy of availability).
\end_layout

